[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1387[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1388[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m---[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1389[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1390[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m##[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mThe Honest Take[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1391[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1392[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe detection problem is technically interesting, and it's a small fraction of what makes this program work. Same lesson as every complex recipe in this chapter, said again because the lesson is the lesson. A great detector with a public health team that can't investigate the clusters produces no value. A simple control-chart detector with an active surveillance program, a clear response chain, and tight cross-jurisdictional coordination produces real value. Build the program first. Build the technology into the program second.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1393[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1394[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe thing that surprised me the first time I worked on syndromic surveillance: the signal-to-noise ratio is genuinely brutal in a way that's hard to internalize until you see it. A typical large county sees thousands of ED visits per day; the leading edge of an outbreak might be three of those visits. You're looking for three excess cases against two thousand routine ones, in a way that doesn't fire dozens of false alarms a day, while staying sensitive enough to catch the outbreak before it grows to thirty (which is when clinicians notice anyway). The math is just hard. The control charts work, but they work because of careful baseline modeling, not because the underlying detection problem is easy.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1395[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1396[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe thing that didn't surprise me but is worth reiterating: baselines are non-stationary in ways that make every year a new problem. Every flu season has a different shape. Every RSV season has a different timing. The post-pandemic baseline is still settling out half a decade after the structural shifts began. A surveillance system that doesn't account for non-stationarity flags every winter as an outbreak. A system that over-corrects misses the year when something genuinely shifts. The right answer is humility: review baseline assumptions every season, validate against the prior year's outcomes, and accept that some years the model will be wrong in informative ways.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1397[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1398[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mMulti-source fusion is the biggest leverage point I've seen in the last decade. Clinical syndromic surveillance alone is noisy. Wastewater alone is noisy. Pharmacy data alone is noisy. School absenteeism alone is noisy. But when three or four of these sources move concordantly, the joint signal is much stronger than any single source. The fusion layer doesn't have to be sophisticated; even a simple "count concordant sources" rule produces substantial precision improvements over single-source detection. The challenge is the engineering work to integrate the sources reliably; once the integrations are in place, the analytic value compounds.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1399[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1400[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mWastewater surveillance changed the field. I was skeptical at first; processing sewage to detect viruses sounded more like a research curiosity than an operational signal. The COVID-19 pandemic proved otherwise. Wastewater can lead clinical surveillance by 5-10 days for many pathogens because it captures sub-clinical and pre-symptomatic infections that don't produce care-seeking. The signal is noisy at the individual sample level, but with reasonable normalization (against PMMoV or population estimates) and modest temporal smoothing, the trend is informative. Programs that have integrated wastewater have a meaningful advantage over programs that haven't.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1401[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1402[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe biggest disappointment in the field, in my view, has been the slow rollout of eCR. The vision (every notifiable condition reported automatically from the EHR to the public health authority through HL7 FHIR) has been clear for a decade. The reality is that adoption is uneven, integration is bespoke per EHR vendor and per jurisdiction, and many providers still report on paper or by fax for some conditions. The technical pieces work; the operational and organizational coordination is hard. Programs that have managed end-to-end eCR for a meaningful set of conditions have a substantial advantage; most programs are somewhere in the middle of the rollout.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1403[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1404[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe thing that surprised me about LLM-assisted triage: it's particularly valuable here, more so than in most clinical AI applications. The cluster-narrative LLM doesn't make detection decisions; it compiles structured evidence into a readable summary. The investigator's day used to be: open the cluster, look at the line list, look at the geographic visualization, check the demographic breakdown, look up the lab context, check whether there's a related sequence cluster, look at multi-source signals, then write a note about whether to investigate. That's twenty to forty minutes per cluster. A well-engineered narrative LLM cuts the per-cluster review time substantially. The investigator still makes the decision; the LLM does the legwork. The productivity gain compounds: more clusters reviewed per day means more thresholds calibrated, more feedback into the system, faster operational learning.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1405[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1406[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe biggest mistake I see: programs that get over-excited about advanced analytics and skimp on the basics. A program with a sophisticated GNN-based cluster detector and incomplete chief-complaint NLP, missing wastewater integration, and no eCR connection produces worse outcomes than a program with classical control charts, well-tuned syndromic classification, integrated wastewater, and active eCR coverage. Get the basics right first. Add the sophistication at the margin, not as a substitute for foundational work.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1407[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1408[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe political reality: this is a public-health-meets-clinical-care joint function, and the two domains have different operational priorities. Clinical infection prevention focuses on facility-level and unit-level signals; public health focuses on community-level signals. Both matter; they're slightly different problems. The most successful programs have explicit joint governance, with clinical infection prevention teams contributing to the surveillance program through shared data, shared methodology, and shared response coordination. Programs run by public health alone tend to under-capture the facility-level signal; programs run by infection prevention alone tend to under-capture the community-level signal.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1409[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1410[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mHonest about the COVID-19 lessons: the pandemic accelerated the field in some ways and exposed durable gaps in others. Wastewater surveillance went from research curiosity to operational pillar. eCR adoption increased. Cross-jurisdictional coordination improved in some places and got worse in others. Genomic surveillance scaled enormously and is now operational for many pathogens. But the fundamental gap between detection and response, between data systems and investigation capacity, between surveillance and public communication, all remained. The technology improved; the institutional infrastructure didn't keep up. A surveillance system that detects faster doesn't produce better outcomes if the response infrastructure can't keep pace. The investment case for surveillance technology is bounded by the response capacity it feeds.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1411[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1412[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe thing nobody talks about: training-data scarcity is a real constraint on what supervised approaches can do here. Confirmed outbreaks are rare; the labels are noisy (an indeterminate cluster doesn't tell the model whether the cluster was real or not); and the false-alarm rate during the early phase of a real outbreak (before lab confirmation) means some "false alarms" in the training data are actually real outbreaks that didn't get adjudicated as such. Most of the actual detection work is statistical (control charts, regression, scan statistics) or rule-based for this reason; supervised re-rankers help at the margin but aren't usually the primary detector.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1413[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1414[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mMature programs treat the false-alarm rate as a leading indicator. A rising false-alarm rate signals one of several things: a structural shift in care-seeking behavior, an EHR upgrade that changed the chief-complaint distribution, a coding-mapping change that shifted syndromic classification, a baseline-data quality issue, or threshold drift. Programs that watch the false-alarm rate as carefully as the true-alarm rate catch the operational drift earlier than programs that don't.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1415[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1416[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe thing I'd do differently: I'd start narrower than I usually have. A program that begins with control-chart detection on 4-6 high-priority syndromes (fever-respiratory, GI, ILI, rash, neuro, sepsis), at the county level, with manual review by a surveillance team of 2-3 epidemiologists, will produce meaningful outcomes within a quarter or two. From that base, regression-based detection, then spatial clustering, then multi-source fusion, then LLM-assisted triage, each in sequence with measured impact. Programs that try to deploy the full multi-detector multi-source system on day one usually end up with a system that's too noisy to use and too complex to tune. Pilot, validate, scale.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1417[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1418[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe financial story is harder to make than for most healthcare AI applications. Surveillance pays off in catastrophe avoidance: an outbreak detected early enough to contain is dollars saved, but the dollars are counterfactual and never visible on a balance sheet. A surveillance program's ROI is measured in outbreaks-not-experienced, which is unmeasurable. The right framing is "we're investing in detection because the cost of a major outbreak we didn't catch in time is unbounded," not "we'll save X dollars per year." That framing works at the public health level (where catastrophe-avoidance is the point of the agency) but is harder at the institutional level (where infection-prevention budgets are easier to justify). Programs that make this argument well include both the operational ROI (time savings on routine investigation, productivity of the surveillance team) and the strategic ROI (catastrophe-avoidance, preparedness for the next pandemic). [38;2;101;115;126m<!--[38;2;101;115;126m TODO (TechWriter): verify recent CDC cost-of-outbreak studies and BARDA-published preparedness ROI estimates for the financial framing here. [38;2;101;115;126m-->[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1419[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1420[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mPeople matter most, even when they're invisible. The clinicians who first see the unusual cases. The school nurses who notice the absences. The lab technicians who see the unusual culture results. The infection preventionists who notice the unit cluster. The epidemiologists who connect the dots. The patients who get sick and get better, or who don't. The surveillance system's purpose is to compress the time between the first case and the response, so that fewer of those patients are part of the next chapter of the outbreak. The operational ethic should reflect that, even when the day-to-day work doesn't bring all of those people into the room.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1421[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[K
